In the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kojiki|qq=}} and the {{ill|Sendai Kuji Hongi|ja|先代旧事本紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sendai Kuji Hongi|qq=}}, Shiomi no Sukune is identified as a descendant of {{ill|Saho no Hikoo no Mikoto|ja|狭穂彦王|1=Sahohiko no Mikoto|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saho no Hikoo no Mikoto|13=User:Immanuelle/Sahohiko no Mikoto|qq=}}, suggesting a connection with the {{ill|Kusakabe clan|ja|日下部氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kusakabe clan|qq=}}.
According to the traditions of {{ill|Sakaorimiya Shrine|ja|酒折宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sakaorimiya Shrine|qq=}}, when {{ill|Yamato Takeru|ja|倭建命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamato Takeru|qq=}} visited Kai Province, he entrusted Shiomi no Sukune with a sacred flint pouch, saying, "May my spirit remain here and be venerated." Shiomi no Sukune established a shrine on the slopes of Tsukimi Mountain, enshrining the flint as the deity. Scholars such as Masayoshi Isogai and Hidesaburō Hara associate the "Elder of Sacred Fires" mentioned in the legends with Shiomi no Sukune.<ref name="#1">Hara, Hidesaburō. "Paths to the East and Royal Authority," in *Ancient Japan Volume 7: Chubu*, Kadokawa Shoten, 1993.</ref>
Shiomi no Sukune appears in the founding legends of numerous historic shrines in Kai Province. For example: - {{ill|Miwa Shrine (Fuefuki)|ja|美和神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miwa Shrine (Fuefuki)|qq=}} is said to have originated when he enshrined the deity {{ill|Ōmononushi|ja|大物主|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōmononushi|qq=}} from the {{ill|Ōmiwa Shrine|ja|大神神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōmiwa Shrine|qq=}} in the Keikō era. - {{ill|Kanazakura Shrine|ja|金櫻神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanazakura Shrine|qq=}} traces its roots to Shiomi no Sukune's construction of a hall for Yamato Takeru's worship in the 40th year of Emperor Keikō's reign. - {{ill|Jinbu Shrine (Yamanashi)|ja|神部神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jinbu Shrine (Yamanashi)|qq=}} attributes its founding to Shiomi no Sukune bringing a deity from Mount Hiei in {{ill|Ōmi Province|ja|近江国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōmi Province|qq=}}. - Nakamaki Shrine was established by Shiomi no Sukune at Emperor Keikō's command after Yamato Takeru's visit to Sakaorimiya Shrine.
Beyond shrines, Shiomi no Sukune is also central to the foundation myth of {{ill|Shimobe Onsen|ja|下部温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shimobe Onsen|qq=}}, which recounts his discovery of the hot springs during a regional inspection.<ref>Japan Spa Association, "[https://www.spa.or.jp/kokumin/971/ Shimobe Onsen]."</ref>
Shiomi no Sukune is enshrined as a deity at {{ill|Kokuritsu Shrine|ja|国立神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kokuritsu Shrine|qq=}}.
== Genealogy ==
Shiomi no Sukune was the child of Chitohiko no Mikoto, the great-grandson of {{ill|Saho no Hikoo no Mikoto|ja|狭穂彦王|1=Sahohiko no Mikoto|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saho no Hikoo no Mikoto|13=User:Immanuelle/Sahohiko no Mikoto|qq=}}.
